# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: commutative-algebra
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Commutative algebra is the main technical tool of algebraic geometry, and many results and concepts of commutative algebra are strongly related with geometrical concepts.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] The study of rings that are not necessarily commutative is known as noncommutative algebra; it includes ring theory, representation theory, and the theory of Banach algebras.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Commutative algebra is essentially the study of the rings occurring in algebraic number theory and algebraic geometry.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Several concepts of commutative algebras have been developed in relation with algebraic number theory, such as Dedekind rings (the main class of commutative rings occurring in algebraic number theory), integral extensions, and valuation rings.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Polynomial rings in several indeterminates over a field are examples of commutative rings.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] An affine algebraic variety corresponds to a prime ideal in a polynomial ring, and the points of such an affine variety correspond to the maximal ideals that contain this prime ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] The Zariski topology, originally defined on an algebraic variety, has been extended to the sets of the prime ideals of any commutative ring; for this topology, the closed sets are the sets of prime ideals that contain a given ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] The spectrum of a ring is a ringed space formed by the prime ideals equipped with the Zariski topology, and the localizations of the ring at the open sets of a basis of this topology.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] This is the starting point of scheme theory, a generalization of algebraic geometry introduced by Grothendieck, which is strongly based on commutative algebra, and has induced, in turns, many developments of commutative algebra.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] The subject, first known as ideal theory, began with Richard Dedekind's work on ideals, itself based on the earlier work of Ernst Kummer and Leopold Kronecker.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Later, David Hilbert introduced the term *ring* to generalize the earlier term *number ring*.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Hilbert introduced a more abstract approach to replace the more concrete and computationally oriented methods grounded in such things as complex analysis and classical invariant theory.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] In turn, Hilbert strongly influenced Emmy Noether, who recast many earlier results in terms of an ascending chain condition, now known as the Noetherian condition.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Another important milestone was the work of Hilbert's student Emanuel Lasker, who introduced primary ideals and proved the first version of the Lasker–Noether theorem.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] The main figure responsible for the birth of commutative algebra as a mature subject was Wolfgang Krull, who introduced the fundamental notions of localization and completion of a ring, as well as that of regular local rings.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] He established the concept of the Krull dimension of a ring, first for Noetherian rings before moving on to expand his theory to cover general valuation rings and Krull rings.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] To this day, Krull's principal ideal theorem is widely considered the single most important foundational theorem in commutative algebra.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] These results paved the way for the introduction of commutative algebra into algebraic geometry, an idea which would revolutionize the latter subject.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Much of the modern development of commutative algebra emphasizes modules.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Both ideals of a ring *R* and *R*-algebras are special cases of *R*-modules, so module theory encompasses both ideal theory and the theory of ring extensions.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Though it was already incipient in Kronecker's work, the modern approach to commutative algebra using module theory is usually credited to Krull and Noether.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] A **Noetherian ring**, named after Emmy Noether, is a ring in which every ideal is finitely generated; that is, all elements of any ideal can be written as a linear combinations of a finite set of elements, with coefficients in the ring.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Many commonly considered commutative rings are Noetherian, in particular, every field, the ring of the integer, and every polynomial ring in one or several indeterminates over them.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] The fact that polynomial rings over a field are Noetherian is called Hilbert's basis theorem.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Moreover, many ring constructions preserve the Noetherian property.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] In particular, if a commutative ring R is Noetherian, the same is true for every polynomial ring over it, and for every quotient ring, localization, or completion of the ring.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] The importance of the Noetherian property lies in its ubiquity and also in the fact that many important theorems of commutative algebra require that the involved rings are Noetherian, This is the case, in particular of Lasker–Noether theorem, the Krull intersection theorem, and Nakayama's lemma.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Furthermore, if a ring is Noetherian, then it satisfies the descending chain condition on prime ideals, which implies that every Noetherian local ring has a finite Krull dimension.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] An ideal *Q* of a ring is said to be *primary* if *Q* is proper and whenever *xy* ∈ *Q*, either *x* ∈ *Q* or *yn* ∈ *Q* for some positive integer *n*.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] In **Z**, the primary ideals are precisely the ideals of the form (*pe*) where *p* is prime and *e* is a positive integer.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Thus, a primary decomposition of (*n*) corresponds to representing (*n*) as the intersection of finitely many primary ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] with *Qi* primary for all *i* and Rad(*Qi*) ≠ Rad(*Qj*) for *i* ≠ *j*.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] For any primary decomposition of *I*, the set of all radicals, that is, the set {Rad(*Q*1), ..., Rad(*Qt*)} remains the same by the Lasker–Noether theorem.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] In fact, it turns out that (for a Noetherian ring) the set is precisely the assassinator of the module *R*/*I*; that is, the set of all annihilators of *R*/*I* (viewed as a module over *R*) that are prime.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] The localization is a formal way to introduce the "denominators" to a given ring or a module.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] where the denominators *s* range in a given subset *S* of *R*.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] The archetypal example is the construction of the ring **Q** of rational numbers from the ring **Z** of integers.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] A completion is any of several related functors on rings and modules that result in complete topological rings and modules.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Completion is similar to localization, and together they are among the most basic tools in analysing commutative rings.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Complete commutative rings have simpler structure than the general ones and Hensel's lemma applies to them.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] The Zariski topology defines a topology on the spectrum of a ring (the set of prime ideals).
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] where *A* is a fixed commutative ring and *I* is an ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] This is defined in analogy with the classical Zariski topology, where closed sets in affine space are those defined by polynomial equations .
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Thus, *V*(*S*) is "the same as" the maximal ideals containing *S*.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Grothendieck's innovation in defining Spec was to replace maximal ideals with all prime ideals; in this formulation it is natural to simply generalize this observation to the definition of a closed set in the spectrum of a ring.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Commutative algebra (in the form of polynomial rings and their quotients, used in the definition of algebraic varieties) has always been a part of algebraic geometry.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] However, in the late 1950s, algebraic varieties were subsumed into Alexander Grothendieck's concept of a scheme.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] The gluing is along the Zariski topology; one can glue within the category of locally ringed spaces, but also, using the Yoneda embedding, within the more abstract category of presheaves of sets over the category of affine schemes.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] The Zariski topology in the set-theoretic sense is then replaced by a Zariski topology in the sense of Grothendieck topology.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Grothendieck introduced Grothendieck topologies having in mind more exotic but geometrically finer and more sensitive examples than the crude Zariski topology, namely the étale topology, and the two flat Grothendieck topologies: fppf and fpqc.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Nowadays some other examples have become prominent, including the Nisnevich topology.
[src:commutative-algebra/commutative-algebra] Sheaves can be furthermore generalized to stacks in the sense of Grothendieck, usually with some additional representability conditions, leading to Artin stacks and, even finer, Deligne–Mumford stacks, both often called algebraic stacks.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In mathematics, and more specifically in computer algebra, computational algebraic geometry, and computational commutative algebra, a **Gröbner basis** is a particular kind of generating set of an ideal in a polynomial ring $K[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}]$ over a field K .
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] A Gröbner basis allows many important properties of the ideal and the associated algebraic variety to be deduced easily, such as the dimension and the number of zeros when it is finite.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Gröbner basis computation is one of the main practical tools for solving systems of polynomial equations and computing the images of algebraic varieties under projections or rational maps.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Gröbner basis computation can be seen as a multivariate, non-linear generalization of both Euclid's algorithm for computing polynomial greatest common divisors, and Gaussian elimination for linear systems.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Gröbner bases were introduced by Bruno Buchberger in his 1965 Ph.D. thesis, which also included an algorithm to compute them (Buchberger's algorithm).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] He named them after his advisor Wolfgang Gröbner.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In 2007, Buchberger received the Association for Computing Machinery's Paris Kanellakis Theory and Practice Award for this work.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] However, the Russian mathematician Nikolai Günther had introduced a similar notion in 1913, published in various Russian mathematical journals.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] These papers were largely ignored by the mathematical community until their rediscovery in 1987 by Bodo Renschuch *et al.* An analogous concept for multivariate power series was developed independently by Heisuke Hironaka in 1964, who named them **standard bases**.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This term has been used by some authors to also denote Gröbner bases.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The theory of Gröbner bases has been extended by many authors in various directions.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] It has been generalized to other structures such as polynomials over principal ideal rings or polynomial rings, and also some classes of non-commutative rings and algebras, like Ore algebras.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Gröbner bases are primarily defined for ideals in a polynomial ring $R=K[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}]$ over a field K.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Although the theory works for any field, most Gröbner basis computations are done either when K is the field of rationals or the integers modulo a prime number.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The vector $A=[a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}]$ is called the *exponent vector* of the monomial.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Monomials are uniquely defined by their exponent vectors, and, when a monomial ordering (see below) is fixed, a polynomial is uniquely represented by the ordered list of the ordered pairs formed by an exponent vector and the corresponding coefficient.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This representation of polynomials is especially efficient for Gröbner basis computation in computers, although it is less convenient for other computations such as polynomial factorization and polynomial greatest common divisor.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] All operations related to Gröbner bases require the choice of a total order on the monomials, with the following properties of compatibility with multiplication.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] A total order satisfying these condition is sometimes called an *admissible ordering*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] These conditions imply that the order is a well-order, that is, every strictly decreasing sequence of monomials is finite.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Gröbner basis theory was initially introduced for the lexicographical ordering.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] It was soon realised that the Gröbner basis for degrevlex is almost always much easier to compute, and that it is almost always easier to compute a lex Gröbner basis by first computing the degrevlex basis and then using a "change of ordering algorithm".
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] When elimination is needed, degrevlex is not convenient; both lex and lexdeg may be used but, again, many computations are relatively easy with lexdeg and almost impossible with lex.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Once a monomial ordering is fixed, the terms of a polynomial (a term is the product of a monomial with its nonzero coefficient) are naturally ordered by decreasing monomials (for this order).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This makes the representation of a polynomial as a sorted list of pairs coefficient–exponent vector a canonical representation of the polynomials (that is, two polynomials are equal if and only if they have the same representation).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The first (greatest) term of a polynomial p for this ordering and the corresponding monomial and coefficient are respectively called the *leading term*, *leading monomial* and *leading coefficient* and denoted, in this article, lt(*p*), lm(*p*) and lc(*p*).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Most polynomial operations related to Gröbner bases involve the leading terms.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] So, the representation of polynomials as sorted lists make these operations particularly efficient (reading the first element of a list takes a constant time, independently of the length of the list).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] One says that M *divides* N, or that N is a *multiple* of M, if $a_{i}\leq b_{i}$ for every i; that is, if A is componentwise not greater than B.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In this case, the quotient ${\textstyle {\frac {N}{M}}}$ is defined as ${\textstyle {\frac {N}{M}}=x_{1}^{b_{1}-a_{1}}\cdots x_{n}^{b_{n}-a_{n}}.}$ In other words, the exponent vector of ${\textstyle {\frac {N}{M}}}$ is the componentwise subtraction of the exponent vectors of N and M.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The *greatest common divisor* gcd(*M*, *N*) of M and N is the monomial ${\textstyle x_{1}^{\min(a_{1},b_{1})}\cdots x_{n}^{\min(a_{n},b_{n})}}$ whose exponent vector is the componentwise minimum of A and B.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The *least common multiple* lcm(*M*, *N*) is defined similarly with max instead of min.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The *reduction* of a polynomial by other polynomials with respect to a monomial ordering is central to Gröbner basis theory.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] It is a generalization of both row reduction occurring in Gaussian elimination and division steps of the Euclidean division of univariate polynomials.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] When completed as much as possible, it is sometimes called **multivariate division** although its result is not uniquely defined.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Let an admissible monomial ordering be fixed, to which refers every monomial comparison that will occur in this section.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] A polynomial f is *lead-reducible* by another polynomial g if the leading monomial lm(*f*) is a multiple of lm(*g*).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The polynomial f is *reducible* by g if some monomial of f is a multiple of lm(*g*).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Suppose that f is *reducible* by g, and let cm be a term of f such that the monomial m is a multiple of lm(*g*).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This operation removes the monomial m from f without changing the terms with a monomial greater than m (for the monomial ordering).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In particular, a *one step lead-reduction* of f produces a polynomial all of whose monomials are smaller than lm(*f*).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Given a finite set G of polynomials, one says that f is *reducible* or *lead-reducible* by G if it is reducible or lead-reducible, respectively, by at least one element g of G.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In this case, a one-step reduction (resp. one-step lead-reduction) of f by G is any one-step reduction (resp. one-step lead-reduction) of f by an element of G.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The (complete) reduction (resp. lead-reduction) of f by G consists of iterating one-step reductions (respect. one-step lead reductions) until getting a polynomial that is irreducible (resp. lead-irreducible) by G.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] It is sometimes called a *normal form* of f by G.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In general this form is not uniquely defined because there are, in general, several elements of G that can be used for reducing f; this non-uniqueness is the starting point of Gröbner basis theory.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] where h is irreducible by G and the $q_{g}$ are polynomials such that $\operatorname {lm} (q_{g}\,g)\leq \operatorname {lm} (f).$ In the case of univariate polynomials, if G consists of a single element g, then h is the remainder of the Euclidean division of f by g, and *q**g* is the quotient.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Moreover, the division algorithm is exactly the process of lead-reduction.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] For this reason, some authors use the term *multivariate division* instead of reduction.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In the example that follows, there are exactly two complete lead-reductions that produce two very different results.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The fact that the results are irreducible (not only lead-irreducible) is specific to the example, although this is rather common with such small examples.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] For the first reduction step, either the first or the second term of f may be reduced.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] However, the reduction of a term amounts to removing this term at the cost of adding new lower terms; if it is not the first reducible term that is reduced, it may occur that a further reduction adds a similar term, which must be reduced again.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] It is therefore always better to reduce first the largest (for the monomial order) reducible term; that is, in particular, to lead-reduce first until getting a lead-irreducible polynomial.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The leading term $-x^{2}y$ of $f_{1}$ is a multiple of the leading monomials of both $g_{1}$ and $g_{2},$ So, one has two choices for the second reduction step.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] It is for dealing with the problems set by this non-uniqueness that Buchberger introduced Gröbner bases and S-polynomials.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Intuitively, $0=f-f$ may be reduced to $f_{2}-f_{3}.$ This implies that $f_{2}-f_{3}$ belongs to the ideal generated by G.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] So, this ideal is not changed by adding $f_{3}-f_{2}$ to G, and this allows more reductions.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In particular, $f_{3}$ can be reduced to $f_{2}$ by $f_{3}-f_{2}$ and this restores the uniqueness of the reduced form.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] where lcm denotes the least common multiple of the leading monomials of f and g.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] where gcd denotes the greatest common divisor of the leading monomials of f and g.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] As the monomials that are reducible by both f and g are exactly the multiples of lcm, one can deal with all cases of non-uniqueness of the reduction by considering only the *S*-polynomials.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This is a fundamental fact for Gröbner basis theory and all algorithms for computing them.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This does not change anything to the theory since the two polynomials are associates.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Let $R=F[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}]$ be a polynomial ring over a field F.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In this section, we suppose that an admissible monomial ordering has been fixed.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Let G be a finite set of polynomials in R that generates an ideal I.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] There are many characterizing properties, which can each be taken as an equivalent definition of Gröbner bases.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] For conciseness, in the following list, the notation "one-word/another word" means that one can take either "one-word" or "another word" for having two different characterizations of Gröbner bases.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Counting the above definition, this provides 12 characterizations of Gröbner bases.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The fact that so many characterizations are possible makes Gröbner bases very useful.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] For every admissible monomial ordering and every finite set G of polynomials, there is a Gröbner basis that contains G and generates the same ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Moreover, such a Gröbner basis may be computed with Buchberger's algorithm.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The algorithm terminates always because of Dickson's lemma or because polynomial rings are Noetherian (Hilbert's basis theorem).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Condition 4 ensures that the result is a Gröbner basis, and the definitions of *S*-polynomials and reduction ensure that the generated ideal is not changed.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The above method is an algorithm for computing Gröbner bases; however, it is very inefficient.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Many improvements of the original Buchberger's algorithm, and several other algorithms have been proposed and implemented, which dramatically improve the efficiency.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] See § Algorithms and implementations, below.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] A Gröbner basis is **minimal** if all leading monomials of its elements are irreducible by the other elements of the basis.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Given a Gröbner basis of an ideal I, one gets a minimal Gröbner basis of I by removing the polynomials whose leading monomials are multiple of the leading monomial of another element of the Gröbner basis.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] However, if two polynomials of the basis have the same leading monomial, only one must be removed.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] So, every Gröbner basis contains a minimal Gröbner basis as a subset.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] All minimal Gröbner bases of a given ideal (for a fixed monomial ordering) have the same number of elements, and the same leading monomials, and the non-minimal Gröbner bases have more elements than the minimal ones.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] A Gröbner basis is **reduced** if every polynomial in it is irreducible by the other elements of the basis, and has 1 as leading coefficient.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] So, every reduced Gröbner basis is minimal, but a minimal Gröbner basis need not be reduced.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] All reduced Gröbner bases of an ideal (for a fixed monomial ordering) are equal.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] It follows that two ideals are equal if and only if they have the same reduced Gröbner basis.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Sometimes, reduced Gröbner bases are defined without the condition on the leading coefficients.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In this case, the uniqueness of reduced Gröbner bases is true only up to the multiplication of polynomials by a nonzero constant.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] When working with polynomials over the field $\mathbb {Q}$ of the rational numbers, it is useful to work only with polynomials with integer coefficients.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In this case, the condition on the leading coefficients in the definition of a reduced basis may be replaced by the condition that all elements of the basis are primitive polynomials with integer coefficients, with positive leading coefficients.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This restores the uniqueness of reduced bases.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] For every monomial ordering, the empty set of polynomials is the unique Gröbner basis of the zero ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] For every monomial ordering, a set of polynomials that contains a nonzero constant is a Gröbner basis of the unit ideal (the whole polynomial ring).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Conversely, every Gröbner basis of the unit ideal contains a nonzero constant.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The reduced Gröbner basis of the unit is formed by the single polynomial 1.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In the case of polynomials in a single variable, there is a unique admissible monomial ordering, the ordering by the degree.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The minimal Gröbner bases are the singletons consisting of a single polynomial.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The reduced Gröbner bases are the monic polynomials.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] As *f*, *k* and h belong to I, and none of them is reducible by the others, none of $\{f,k\},$ $\{f,h\},$ and $\{h,k\}$ is a Gröbner basis of I.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] can be reduced to zero by *f*, *k* and h.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The method that has been used here for finding h and k, and proving that {*f*, *k*, *h*} is a Gröbner basis is a direct application of Buchberger's algorithm.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] So, it can be applied mechanically to any similar example, although, in general, there are many polynomials and S-polynomials to consider, and the computation is generally too large for being done without a computer.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Unless explicitly stated, all the results that follow are true for any monomial ordering (see that article for the definitions of the different orders that are mentioned below).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] It is a common misconception that the lexicographical order is needed for some of these results.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Reduced Gröbner bases are *unique* for any given ideal and any monomial ordering.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Thus two ideals are equal if and only if they have the same (reduced) Gröbner basis (usually a Gröbner basis software always produces reduced Gröbner bases).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The reduction of a polynomial *f* by the Gröbner basis *G* of an ideal I yields 0 if and only if *f* is in I.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This allows to test the membership of an element in an ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Another method consists in verifying that the Gröbner basis of *G*∪{*f*} is equal to *G*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] To test if the ideal I generated by *f*1, ..., *f**k* is contained in the ideal J, it suffices to test that every *f**I* is in J.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] One may also test the equality of the reduced Gröbner bases of J and *J* ∪ {*f*1, ...,*f**k*}.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Any set of polynomials may be viewed as a system of polynomial equations by equating the polynomials to zero.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The set of the solutions of such a system depends only on the generated ideal, and, therefore does not change when the given generating set is replaced by the Gröbner basis, for any ordering, of the generated ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Such a solution, with coordinates in an algebraically closed field containing the coefficients of the polynomials, is called a *zero of the ideal*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In the usual case of rational coefficients, this algebraically closed field is chosen as the complex field.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] An ideal does not have any zero (the system of equations is inconsistent) if and only if 1 belongs to the ideal (this is Hilbert's Nullstellensatz), or, equivalently, if its Gröbner basis (for any monomial ordering) contains 1, or, also, if the corresponding reduced Gröbner basis is [1].
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Given the Gröbner basis *G* of an ideal *I*, it has only a finite number of zeros, if and only if, for each variable *x*, *G* contains a polynomial with a leading monomial that is a power of *x* (without any other variable appearing in the leading term).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] If this is the case, then the number of zeros, counted with multiplicity, is equal to the number of monomials that are not multiples of any leading monomial of *G*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This number is called the *degree* of the ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] When the number of zeros is finite, the Gröbner basis for a lexicographical monomial ordering provides, theoretically, a solution: the first coordinate of a solution is a root of the greatest common divisor of polynomials of the basis that depend only on the first variable.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] After substituting this root in the basis, the second coordinate of this solution is a root of the greatest common divisor of the resulting polynomials that depend only on the second variable, and so on.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This solving process is only theoretical, because it implies GCD computation and root-finding of polynomials with approximate coefficients, which are not practicable because of numeric instability.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Therefore, other methods have been developed to solve polynomial systems through Gröbner bases (see System of polynomial equations for more details).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The **dimension** of an ideal *I* in a polynomial ring *R* is the Krull dimension of the ring *R*/*I* and is equal to the dimension of the algebraic set of the zeros of *I*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] It is also equal to number of hyperplanes in general position which are needed to have an intersection with the algebraic set, which is a finite number of points.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The **degree** of the ideal and of its associated algebraic set is the number of points of this finite intersection, counted with multiplicity.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In particular, the degree of a hypersurface is equal to the degree of its definition polynomial.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The dimension depend only on the set of the leading monomials of the Gröbner basis of the ideal for any monomial ordering.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The same is true for the degree and degree-compatible monomial orderings; a monomial ordering is *degree compatible* if smaller for the degree implies smaller for the monomial ordering.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The dimension is the maximal size of a subset *S* of the variables such that there is no leading monomial depending only on the variables in *S*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Thus, if the ideal has dimension 0, then for each variable *x* there is a leading monomial in the Gröbner basis that is a power of x.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Both dimension and degree may be deduced from the Hilbert series of the ideal, which is the series ${\textstyle \sum _{i=0}^{\infty }d_{i}t^{i}}$ , where $d_{i}$ is the number of monomials of degree *i* that are not multiple of any leading monomial in the Gröbner basis.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] where *d* is the dimension of the ideal and $P(t)$ is a polynomial.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The number $P(1)$ is the degree of the algebraic set defined by the ideal, in the case of a homogeneous ideal or a monomial ordering compatible with the degree; that is, to compare two monomials, one compares their total degrees first.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The dimension does not depend on the choice of a monomial ordering, although the Hilbert series and the polynomial $P(t)$ may change with changes of the monomial ordering.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] However, for homogeneous ideals or monomial orderings compatible with the degree, the Hilbert series and the polynomial $P(t)$ do not depend on the choice of monomial ordering.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Most computer algebra systems that provide functions to compute Gröbner bases provide also functions for computing the Hilbert series, and thus also the dimension and the degree.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The computation of Gröbner bases for an *elimination* monomial ordering allows computational elimination theory.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Consider a polynomial ring $K[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n},y_{1},\ldots ,y_{m}]=K[X,Y],$ in which the variables are split into two subsets *X* and *Y*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Let us also choose an elimination monomial ordering "eliminating" *X*, that is a monomial ordering for which two monomials are compared by comparing first the *X*-parts, and, in case of equality only, considering the *Y*-parts.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This implies that a monomial containing an *X*-variable is greater than every monomial independent of *X*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] If *G* is a Gröbner basis of an ideal *I* for this monomial ordering, then $G\cap K[Y]$ is a Gröbner basis of $I\cap K[Y]$ (this ideal is often called the *elimination ideal*).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Moreover, $G\cap K[Y]$ consists exactly of the polynomials of *G* whose leading terms belong to *K*[*Y*] (this makes the computation of $G\cap K[Y]$ very easy, as only the leading monomials need to be checked).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This *elimination property* has many applications, some described in the next sections.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The lexicographical ordering such that $x_{1}>\cdots >x_{n}$ is an elimination ordering for every partition $\{x_{1},\ldots ,x_{k}\},\{x_{k+1},\ldots ,x_{n}\}.$ Thus a Gröbner basis for this ordering carries much more information than usually necessary.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This may explain why Gröbner bases for the lexicographical ordering are usually the most difficult to compute.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] If I and J are two ideals generated respectively by {*f*1, ..., *f**m*} and {*g*1, ..., *g**k*}, then a single Gröbner basis computation produces a Gröbner basis of their intersection *I* ∩ *J*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] For this, one introduces a new indeterminate *t*, and one uses an elimination ordering such that the first block contains only *t* and the other block contains all the other variables (this means that a monomial containing *t* is greater than every monomial that does not contain *t*).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In other words, *I* ∩ *J* is obtained by *eliminating* *t* in *K*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This may be proven by observing that the ideal *K* consists of the polynomials $(a-b)t+b$ such that $a\in I$ and $b\in J$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] One may (and will) suppose that $f_{i}(t)$ and $g_{i}(t)$ are coprime (they have no non-constant common factors).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Implicitization consists in computing the implicit equations of such a curve.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In case of *n* = 2, that is for plane curves, this may be computed with the resultant.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In the other case, the resultant is a power of the result of the elimination.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] When modeling a problem by polynomial equations, it is often assumed that some quantities are non-zero, so as to avoid degenerate cases.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] For example, when dealing with triangles, many properties become false if the triangle degenerates to a line segment, i.e. the length of one side is equal to the sum of the lengths of the other sides.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In such situations, one cannot deduce relevant information from the polynomial system unless the degenerate solutions are ignored.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] More precisely, the system of equations defines an algebraic set which may have several irreducible components, and one must remove the components on which the degeneracy conditions are everywhere zero.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This is done by *saturating* the equations by the degeneracy conditions, which may be done via the elimination property of Gröbner bases.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The localization of a ring consists in adjoining to it the formal inverses of some elements.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This section concerns only the case of a single element, or equivalently a finite number of elements (adjoining the inverses of several elements is equivalent to adjoining the inverse of their product).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The *localization* of a ring *R* by an element *f* is the ring $R_{f}=R[t]/(1-ft),$ where *t* is a new indeterminate representing the inverse of *f*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The *localization* of an ideal I of *R* is the ideal $I_{f}=R_{f}I$ of $R_{f}.$ When *R* is a polynomial ring, computing in $R_{f}$ is not efficient because of the need to manage the denominators.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Therefore, localization is usually replaced by the operation of *saturation*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] If J is the ideal generated by I and 1−*ft* in *R*[*t*], then $I:f^{\infty }=J\cap R.$ It follows that, if *R* is a polynomial ring, a Gröbner basis computation eliminating *t* produces a Gröbner basis of the saturation of an ideal by a polynomial.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Instead of using *F*, one may also start from a Gröbner basis of *F*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Which method is most efficient depends on the problem.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] However, if the saturation does not remove any component, that is if the ideal is equal to its saturated ideal, computing first the Gröbner basis of *F* is usually faster.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] On the other hand, if the saturation removes some components, the direct computation may be dramatically faster.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Hilbert's Nullstellensatz has two versions.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The first one asserts that a set of polynomials has no common zeros over an algebraic closure of the field of the coefficients, if and only if 1 belongs to the generated ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This is easily tested with a Gröbner basis computation, because 1 belongs to an ideal if and only if 1 belongs to the Gröbner basis of the ideal, for any monomial ordering.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The second version asserts that the set of common zeros (in an algebraic closure of the field of the coefficients) of an ideal is contained in the hypersurface of the zeros of a polynomial *f*, if and only if a power of *f* belongs to the ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This may be tested by saturating the ideal by *f*; in fact, a power of *f* belongs to the ideal if and only if the saturation by *f* provides a Gröbner basis containing 1.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] One could guess that it suffices to eliminate the parameters to obtain the implicit equations of the variety, as it has been done in the case of curves.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Unfortunately this is not always the case.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] If the $p_{i}$ have a common zero (sometimes called *base point*), every irreducible component of the non-empty algebraic set defined by the $p_{i}$ is an irreducible component of the algebraic set defined by *I*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] It follows that, in this case, the direct elimination of the $t_{i}$ provides an empty set of polynomials.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Eliminate the $t_{i}$ from G to get a Gröbner basis of the ideal (of the implicit equations) of the variety.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Buchberger's algorithm is the oldest algorithm for computing Gröbner bases.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] It was devised by Bruno Buchberger together with the Gröbner basis theory.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] It is straightforward to implement, but it appeared soon that raw implementations can solve only trivial problems.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The integers occurring during a computation may be sufficiently large for making fast multiplication algorithms and multimodular arithmetic useful.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] For this reason, most optimized implementations use the GMP library.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The choice of the S-polynomials to reduce and of the polynomials used for reducing them is devoted to heuristics.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] As in many computational problems, heuristics cannot detect most hidden simplifications, and if heuristic choices are avoided, one may get a dramatic improvement of the algorithm efficiency.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In most cases most S-polynomials that are computed are reduced to zero; that is, most computing time is spent to compute zero.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The monomial ordering that is most often needed for the applications (pure lexicographic) is not the ordering that leads to the easiest computation, generally the ordering *degrevlex*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] For solving 3. many improvements, variants and heuristics have been proposed before the introduction of F4 and F5 algorithms by Jean-Charles Faugère.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] As these algorithms are designed for integer coefficients or with coefficients in the integers modulo a prime number, Buchberger's algorithm remains useful for more general coefficients.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Roughly speaking, F4 algorithm solves 3. by replacing many S-polynomial reductions by the row reduction of a single large matrix for which advanced methods of linear algebra can be used.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This solves partially issue 4., as reductions to zero in Buchberger's algorithm correspond to relations between rows of the matrix to be reduced, and the zero rows of the reduced matrix correspond to a basis of the vector space of these relations.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] F5 algorithm improves F4 by introducing a criterion that allows reducing the size of the matrices to be reduced.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This criterion is almost optimal, since the matrices to be reduced have full rank in sufficiently regular cases (in particular, when the input polynomials form a regular sequence).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Tuning F5 for a general use is difficult, since its performances depend on an order on the input polynomials and a balance between the incrementation of the working polynomial degree and of the number of the input polynomials that are considered.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] To date (2022), there is no distributed implementation that is significantly more efficient than F4, but, over modular integers F5 has been used successfully for several cryptographic challenges; for example, for breaking HFE challenge.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Issue 5. has been solved by the discovery of basis conversion algorithms that start from the Gröbner basis for one monomial ordering for computing a Gröbner basis for another monomial ordering.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] FGLM algorithm is such a basis conversion algorithm that works only in the zero-dimensional case (where the polynomials have a finite number of complex common zeros) and has a polynomial complexity in the number of common zeros.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] A basis conversion algorithm that works is the general case is the *Gröbner walk algorithm*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In its original form, FGLM may be the critical step for solving systems of polynomial equations because FGML does not take into account the sparsity of involved matrices.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This has been fixed by the introduction of *sparse FGLM algorithms*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] When F4 is available, it is generally much more efficient than Buchberger's algorithm.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The implementation techniques and algorithmic variants are not always documented, although they may have a dramatic effect on efficiency.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Implementations of F4 and (sparse)-FGLM are included in the library *Msolve*.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Beside Gröbner algorithms, Msolve contains fast algorithms for real-root isolation, and combines all these functions in an algorithm for the real solutions of systems of polynomial equations that outperforms dramatically the other software for this problem (Maple and Magma).
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Msolve is available on GitHub, and is interfaced with Julia, Maple and SageMath; this means that Msolve can be used directly from within these software environments.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The complexity of the Gröbner basis computations is commonly evaluated in term of the number n of variables and the maximal degree d of the input polynomials.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In the worst case, the main parameter of the complexity is the maximal degree of the elements of the resulting reduced Gröbner basis.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The worst-case complexity of a Gröbner basis computation is doubly exponential in n.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] As every algorithm for computing a Gröbner basis must write its result, this provides a lower bound of the complexity.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The concept and algorithms of Gröbner bases have been generalized to submodules of free modules over a polynomial ring.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] In fact, if L is a free module over a ring R, then one may consider the direct sum $R\oplus L$ as a ring by defining the product of two elements of L to be 0.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] This allows identifying a submodule of L generated by $g_{1},\ldots ,g_{k}$ with the ideal of $R[e_{1},\ldots ,e_{l}]$ generated by $g_{1},\ldots ,g_{k}$ and the products $e_{i}e_{j}$ , $1\leq i\leq j\leq l$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] If R is a polynomial ring, this reduces the theory and the algorithms of Gröbner bases of modules to the theory and the algorithms of Gröbner bases of ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] The concept and algorithms of Gröbner bases have also been generalized to ideals over various rings, commutative or not, like polynomial rings over a principal ideal ring or Weyl algebras.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Gröbner bases have been applied in the theory of error-correcting codes for algebraic decoding.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] By using Gröbner basis computation on various forms of error-correcting equations, decoding methods were developed for correcting errors of cyclic codes, affine variety codes, algebraic-geometric codes and even general linear block codes.
[src:commutative-algebra/gröbner-basis] Applying Gröbner basis in algebraic decoding is still a research area of channel coding theory.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] In mathematics, **Hilbert's Nullstellensatz** (German for "theorem of zeros" or, more literally, "zero-locus-theorem") is a theorem that establishes a fundamental relationship between geometry and algebra.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] It was proven by David Hilbert in his second major paper on invariant theory in 1893 (following his seminal 1890 paper in which he proved Hilbert's basis theorem) and became a foundational result of algebraic geometry.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] There are several formulations of the Nullstellensatz, the most elementary of which deal with conditions for the existence of solutions to systems of multivariate polynomial equations over an algebraically closed field (such as the complex numbers $\mathbb {C}$ ).
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] The **weak Nullstellensatz** is a corollary (or a lemma, depending which is proved first) of the Nullstellensatz which can be stated as follows.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] in the variables $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ , where $f_{1},\dots ,f_{m}\in K[x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}]$ are multivariate polynomials over an algebraically closed field K .
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Since the expression on the left-hand side must evaluate to 0 at any $(x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})$ that solves the system of equations, it is obvious from the inconsistency that no solution can exist if this condition holds.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Informally, the (weak) Nullstellensatz asserts that in the absence of such an inconsistency, a solution to the system of equations must exist.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Let *k* be a field (such as the rational numbers) and *K* be an algebraically closed field extension of *k* (such as the complex numbers).
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Consider the polynomial ring $k[X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}]$ and let *J* be an ideal in this ring.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] The algebraic set $\mathrm {V} (J)$ defined by this ideal consists of all *n*-tuples $a=(a_{1},\dots ,a_{n})$ in $K^{n}$ such that $f(a)=0$ for all $f\in J$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Hilbert's Nullstellensatz states that if *p* is a polynomial in $k[X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}]$ that vanishes on the algebraic set $\mathrm {V} (J)$ , i.e., $p(a)=0$ for all $a\in \mathrm {V} (J)$ , then there exists a natural number r such that $p^{r}\in J$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] The assertion that ${\hbox{I}}({\hbox{V}}(J))\subseteq {\sqrt {J}}$ is equivalent to the first formulation above with *k* = *K* algebraically closed, while the opposite inclusion is a straightforward consequence of the definitions.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] An immediate corollary is the **weak Nullstellensatz**: If *J* is a proper ideal in $k[X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}]$ , then $\mathrm {V} (J)$ is nonempty, i.e., for every algebraically closed extension $K\supseteq k$ , there exists a common zero in $K^{n}$ for all the polynomials in the ideal *J*.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] This is the reason for the name of the theorem, the full version of which can be proved easily from the 'weak' form using the Rabinowitsch trick.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Specializing to the case of a single polynomial when $K=\mathbb {C}$ and $n=1$ , one immediately recovers a restatement of the fundamental theorem of algebra: A polynomial *P* in $\mathbb {C} [X]$ has a root in $\mathbb {C}$ if and only if $\deg P\neq 0$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] For this reason, the (weak) Nullstellensatz applied to $K=\mathbb {C}$ can be thought of as a generalization of the fundamental theorem of algebra to systems of multivariable polynomial equations.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] As a particular example, consider an algebraic set consisting of a single point $a=(a_{1},\dots ,a_{n})\in K^{n}$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Conversely, every maximal ideal of the polynomial ring $K[X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}]$ (note that K is algebraically closed) is of the form $(X_{1}-a_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}-a_{n})$ for some $a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}\in K$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] This characterization of maximal ideals of polynomial rings over algebraically closed fields is another common formulation of the weak Nullstellensatz.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] As another example of this correspondence and a consequence of the Nullstellensatz, one can show that an algebraic subset *W* in *$K^{n}$* is irreducible (in the Zariski topology) if and only if $\mathrm {I} (W)$ is a prime ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] where the first intersection is taken over maximal ideals ${\mathfrak {m}}\subsetneq K[X_{1},...,X_{n}]$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] This relationship is yet another common formulation of the Nullstellensatz.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] There are many known proofs of the theorem.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Some are non-constructive, such as the first one.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Others are constructive, as based on algorithms for expressing 1 or *pr* as a linear combination of the generators of the ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Zariski's lemma asserts that if a field is finitely generated as an associative algebra over a field *K*, then it is a finite field extension of *K* (that is, it is also finitely generated as a vector space).
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] If *K* is an algebraically closed field and ${\mathfrak {m}}$ is a maximal ideal of the ring of polynomials $K[X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}]$ , then Zariski's lemma implies that $K[X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}]/{\mathfrak {m}}$ is a finite field extension of *K*, and thus, by algebraic closure, must be *K*.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Because of this close relationship, some texts refer to Zariski's lemma as the weak Nullstellensatz or as the 'algebraic version' of the weak Nullstellensatz.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] The full Nullstellensatz can also be proved directly from Zariski's lemma without employing the Rabinowitsch trick.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Here is a sketch of a proof using this lemma.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Let $A=K[X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}]$ for algebraically closed field *K*, and let *J* be an ideal of *A* and $V=\mathrm {V} (J)$ be the common zeros of *J* in $K^{n}$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Recall that $\mathrm {I} (V)$ is radical, and therefore ${\sqrt {J}}\subseteq \mathrm {I} (V)$ , where $\mathrm {I} (V)$ is the ideal of polynomials in *A* vanishing on *V*.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] To show the opposite inclusion, let $f\not \in {\sqrt {J}}$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Then $f\not \in {\mathfrak {p}}$ for some prime ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}\supseteq J$ in *A*.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Let $R=(A/{\mathfrak {p}})[1/{\bar {f}}]$ , where ${\bar {f}}$ is the image of *f* under the natural map $A\to A/{\mathfrak {p}}$ , and ${\mathfrak {m}}$ be a maximal ideal in *R*.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] By Zariski's lemma, $R/{\mathfrak {m}}$ is a finite extension of *K*, and thus, is *K* since *K* is algebraically closed.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Let $x_{i}$ be the images of $X_{i}$ under the natural map $A\to A/{\mathfrak {p}}\to R\to R/{\mathfrak {m}}\cong K$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] The following constructive proof of the weak form is one of the oldest proofs (the strong form results from the Rabinowitsch trick, which is also constructive).
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] If the ideal is principal, generated by a non-constant polynomial p that depends on x, one chooses arbitrary values for the other variables.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] The fundamental theorem of algebra asserts that this choice can be extended to a zero of p.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] In the case of several polynomials $p_{1},\ldots ,p_{n},$ a linear change of variables allows to suppose that $p_{1}$ is monic in the first variable x.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] This proves the weak Nullstellensatz by induction on the number of variables.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] A Gröbner basis is an algorithmic concept that was introduced in 1973 by Bruno Buchberger.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] It is presently fundamental in computational geometry.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] A Gröbner basis is a special generating set of an ideal from which most properties of the ideal can easily be extracted.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] The Nullstellensatz is subsumed by a systematic development of the theory of Jacobson rings, which are those rings in which every radical ideal is an intersection of maximal ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Given Zariski's lemma, proving the Nullstellensatz amounts to showing that if *k* is a field, then every finitely generated *k*-algebra *R* (necessarily of the form ${\textstyle R=k[t_{1},\cdots ,t_{n}]/I}$ ) is Jacobson.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] In all of its variants, Hilbert's Nullstellensatz asserts that some polynomial g belongs or not to an ideal generated, say, by *f*1, ..., *fk*; we have *g* = *f r* in the strong version, *g* = 1 in the weak form.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] This means the existence or the non-existence of polynomials *g*1, ..., *gk* such that *g* = *f*1*g*1 + ... + *fkgk*.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] The usual proofs of the Nullstellensatz are not constructive, non-effective, in the sense that they do not give any way to compute the *gi*.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] It is thus a rather natural question to ask if there is an effective way to compute the *gi* (and the exponent r in the strong form) or to prove that they do not exist.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] To solve this problem, it suffices to provide an upper bound on the total degree of the *gi*: such a bound reduces the problem to a finite system of linear equations that may be solved by usual linear algebra techniques.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Any such upper bound is called an **effective Nullstellensatz**.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] A related problem is the **ideal membership problem**, which consists in testing if a polynomial belongs to an ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] For this problem also, a solution is provided by an upper bound on the degree of the *gi*.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] A general solution of the ideal membership problem provides an effective Nullstellensatz, at least for the weak form.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] In 1925, Grete Hermann gave an upper bound for ideal membership problem that is doubly exponential in the number of variables.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] In 1982 Mayr and Meyer gave an example where the *gi* have a degree that is at least double exponential, showing that every general upper bound for the ideal membership problem is doubly exponential in the number of variables.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Since most mathematicians at the time assumed the effective Nullstellensatz was at least as hard as ideal membership, few mathematicians sought a bound better than double-exponential.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Dale Brownawell gave an upper bound for the effective Nullstellensatz that is simply exponential in the number of variables.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Brownawell's proof relied on analytic techniques valid only in characteristic 0, but, one year later, János Kollár gave a purely algebraic proof, valid in any characteristic, of a slightly better bound.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] This bound is optimal if all the degrees are greater than 2.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] His bound improves Kollár's as soon as at least two of the degrees that are involved are lower than 3.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] We can formulate a certain correspondence between homogeneous ideals of polynomials and algebraic subsets of a projective space, called the **projective Nullstellensatz**, that is analogous to the affine one.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] To do that, we introduce some notations.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] is called the *maximal homogeneous ideal* (see also irrelevant ideal).
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] This implies that the homogeneous components of *f* are also zero on *S* and thus that $\operatorname {I} _{\mathbb {P} ^{n}}(S)$ is a homogeneous ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] Equivalently, $\operatorname {I} _{\mathbb {P} ^{n}}(S)$ is the homogeneous ideal generated by homogeneous polynomials *f* that vanish on *S*.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] where two subsets $X,Y\subseteq \mathbb {C} ^{n}$ are considered equivalent if $X\cap U=Y\cap U$ for some neighborhood *U* of 0.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] It is well-defined; i.e., is independent of a choice of the generators.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] where the left-hand side is the radical of *I*.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] In scheme theory, V and I are generalized and redefined so that they could be applied to subsets of arbitrary commutative (unital) rings and their *prime* spectra, respectively.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] where the last equality follows from a standard property of prime ideals from commutative algebra.
[src:commutative-algebra/hilbert-s-nullstellensatz] In analogy to zero loci in the classical theory, the $\mathbb {V} (S)$ are used to define the closed sets in the Zariski topology of $\mathrm {Spec} \ A$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] In commutative algebra, the **Krull dimension** of a commutative ring *R*, named after Wolfgang Krull, is the supremum of the lengths of all chains of prime ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] The Krull dimension need not be finite even for a Noetherian ring.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] More generally the Krull dimension can be defined for modules over possibly non-commutative rings as the deviation of the poset of submodules.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] The Krull dimension was introduced to provide an algebraic definition of the dimension of an algebraic variety: the dimension of the affine variety defined by an ideal *I* in a polynomial ring *R* is the Krull dimension of *R*/*I*.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] A field *k* has Krull dimension 0; more generally, *k*[*x*1, ..., *x**n*] has Krull dimension *n*.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] A principal ideal domain that is not a field has Krull dimension 1.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] A local ring has Krull dimension 0 if and only if every element of its maximal ideal is nilpotent.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] There are several other ways that have been used to define the dimension of a ring.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] Most of them coincide with the Krull dimension for Noetherian rings, but can differ for non-Noetherian rings.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] We say that a chain of prime ideals of the form ${\mathfrak {p}}_{0}\subsetneq {\mathfrak {p}}_{1}\subsetneq \ldots \subsetneq {\mathfrak {p}}_{n}$ has **length n**.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] That is, the length is the number of strict inclusions, not the number of primes; these differ by 1 .
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] We define the **Krull dimension** of R to be the supremum of the lengths of all chains of prime ideals in R .
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] In other words, the height of ${\mathfrak {p}}$ is the Krull dimension of the localization of R at ${\mathfrak {p}}$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] A prime ideal has height zero if and only if it is a minimal prime ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] The Krull dimension of a ring is the supremum of the heights of all maximal ideals, or those of all prime ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] The height is also sometimes called the codimension, rank, or altitude of a prime ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] In a Noetherian ring, every prime ideal has finite height.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] Nonetheless, Nagata gave an example of a Noetherian ring of infinite Krull dimension.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] A ring is called universally catenary if any finitely generated algebra over it is catenary.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] Nagata gave an example of a Noetherian ring which is not catenary.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] In a Noetherian ring, a prime ideal has height at most n if and only if it is a minimal prime ideal over an ideal generated by n elements (Krull's height theorem and its converse).
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] It implies that the descending chain condition holds for prime ideals in such a way the lengths of the chains descending from a prime ideal are bounded by the number of generators of the prime.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] More generally, the height of an ideal I is the infimum of the heights of all prime ideals containing I .
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] In the language of algebraic geometry, this is the codimension of the subvariety of $\mathrm {Spec} (R)$ corresponding to I .
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] If R is a commutative ring, and M is an R -module, we define the Krull dimension of M to be the Krull dimension of the quotient of R making M a faithful module.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] where $\operatorname {Ann} _{R}(M)$ , the annihilator, is the kernel of the natural map $R\to \operatorname {End} _{R}(M)$ of R into the ring of R -linear endomorphisms of M .
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] In the language of schemes, finitely generated modules are interpreted as coherent sheaves, or generalized finite rank vector bundles.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] The Krull dimension of a module over a possibly non-commutative ring is defined as the deviation of the poset of submodules ordered by inclusion.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] For commutative Noetherian rings, this is the same as the definition using chains of prime ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/krull-dimension] The two definitions can be different for commutative rings which are not Noetherian.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] In commutative algebra and algebraic geometry, **localization** is a formal way to introduce the "denominators" to a given ring or module.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] That is, it introduces a new ring/module out of an existing ring/module *R*, so that it consists of fractions ${\frac {m}{s}},$ such that the denominator *s* belongs to a given subset *S* of *R*.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] If *S* is the set of the non-zero elements of an integral domain, then the localization is the field of fractions: this case generalizes the construction of the field $\mathbb {Q}$ of rational numbers from the ring $\mathbb {Z}$ of integers.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The technique has become fundamental, particularly in algebraic geometry, as it provides a natural link to sheaf theory.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The resulting ring $S^{-1}R$ contains information about the behavior of *V* near *p*, and excludes information that is not "local", such as the zeros of functions that are outside *V* (cf. the example given at local ring).
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The localization of a commutative ring R by a multiplicatively closed set S is a new ring $S^{-1}R$ whose elements are fractions with numerators in R and denominators in S.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] If the ring is an integral domain the construction generalizes and follows closely that of the field of fractions, and, in particular, that of the rational numbers as the field of fractions of the integers.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] For rings that have zero divisors, the construction is similar but requires more care.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Localization is commonly done with respect to a multiplicatively closed set S (also called a *multiplicative set* or a *multiplicative system*) of elements of a ring R, that is a subset of R that is closed under multiplication, and contains 1.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The requirement that S must be a multiplicative set is natural, since it implies that all denominators introduced by the localization belong to S.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The localization by a set U that is not multiplicatively closed can also be defined, by taking as possible denominators all products of elements of U.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] However, the same localization is obtained by using the multiplicatively closed set S of all products of elements of U.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] As this often makes reasoning and notation simpler, it is standard practice to consider only localizations by multiplicative sets.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] For example, the localization by a single element s introduces fractions of the form ${\tfrac {a}{s}},$ but also products of such fractions, such as ${\tfrac {ab}{s^{2}}}.$ So, the denominators will belong to the multiplicative set $\{1,s,s^{2},s^{3},\ldots \}$ of the powers of s.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Therefore, one generally talks of "the localization by the powers of an element" rather than of "the localization by an element".
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] When the ring R is an integral domain and S does not contain 0, the ring $S^{-1}R$ is a subring of the field of fractions of R.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] As such, the localization of a domain is a domain.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] For example, the decimal fractions are the localization of the ring of integers by the multiplicative set of the powers of ten.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] In this case, $S^{-1}R$ consists of the rational numbers that can be written as ${\tfrac {n}{10^{k}}},$ where n is an integer, and k is a nonnegative integer.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] In the general case, a problem arises with zero divisors.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Let S be a multiplicative set in a commutative ring R.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The localization $S^{-1}R$ is defined as the set of the equivalence classes for this relation.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] known as the *canonical localization map*, defines a ring homomorphism from R into $S^{-1}R,$ which is injective if and only if S does not contain any zero divisors.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] If $0\in S,$ then $S^{-1}R$ is the zero ring that has only one unique element 0.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] If S is the set of all regular elements of R (that is the elements that are not zero divisors), $S^{-1}R$ is called the total ring of fractions of R.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The (above defined) ring homomorphism $j\colon R\to S^{-1}R$ satisfies a universal property that is described below.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] This characterizes $S^{-1}R$ up to an isomorphism.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] So all properties of localizations can be deduced from the universal property, independently from the way they have been constructed.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Moreover, many important properties of localization are easily deduced from the general properties of universal properties, while their direct proof may be more technical.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Using category theory, this can be expressed by saying that localization is a functor that is left adjoint to a forgetful functor.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] More precisely, let ${\mathcal {C}}$ and ${\mathcal {D}}$ be the categories whose objects are pairs of a commutative ring and a submonoid of, respectively, the multiplicative monoid or the group of units of the ring.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The morphisms of these categories are the ring homomorphisms that map the submonoid of the first object into the submonoid of the second one.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Finally, let ${\mathcal {F}}\colon {\mathcal {D}}\to {\mathcal {C}}$ be the forgetful functor that forgets that the elements of the second element of the pair are invertible.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] This may seem a rather tricky way of expressing the universal property, but it is useful for showing easily many properties, by using the fact that the composition of two left adjoint functors is a left adjoint functor.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Localization is a rich construction that has many useful properties.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] In this section, only the properties relative to rings and to a single localization are considered.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Properties concerning ideals, modules, or several multiplicative sets are considered in other sections.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] if and only if its total ring of fractions is reduced.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] where the first intersection is over all prime ideals and the second over the maximal ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Let $S\subseteq R$ be a multiplicative set.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The multiplicative set S is *saturated* if it equals its saturation, that is, if ${\hat {S}}=S$ , or equivalently, if $rs\in S$ implies that r and s are in S.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] If S and T are two multiplicative sets, then $S^{-1}R$ and $T^{-1}R$ are isomorphic if and only if they have the same saturation, or, equivalently, if s belongs to one of the multiplicative sets, then there exists $t\in R$ such that st belongs to the other.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Saturated multiplicative sets are not widely used explicitly, since, for verifying that a set is saturated, one must know *all* units of the ring.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The term *localization* originates in the general trend of modern mathematics to study geometrical and topological objects *locally*, that is in terms of their behavior near each point.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Examples of this trend are the fundamental concepts of manifolds, germs and sheafs.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] In algebraic geometry, an affine algebraic set can be identified with a quotient ring of a polynomial ring in such a way that the points of the algebraic set correspond to the maximal ideals of the ring (this is Hilbert's Nullstellensatz).
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] This correspondence has been generalized for making the set of the prime ideals of a commutative ring a topological space equipped with the Zariski topology; this topological space is called the spectrum of the ring.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] In this context, a *localization* by a multiplicative set may be viewed as the restriction of the spectrum of a ring to the subspace of the prime ideals (viewed as *points*) that do not intersect the multiplicative set.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] In number theory and algebraic topology, when working over the ring $\mathbb {Z}$ of integers, one refers to a property relative to an integer n as a property true *at* n or *away* from n, depending on the localization that is considered.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] "**Away from** n" means that the property is considered after localization by the powers of n, and, if p is a prime number, "at p" means that the property is considered after localization at the prime ideal $p\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] This terminology can be explained by the fact that, if p is prime, the nonzero prime ideals of the localization of $\mathbb {Z}$ are either the singleton set {*p*} or its complement in the set of prime numbers.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Let S be a multiplicative set in a commutative ring R, and $j\colon R\to S^{-1}R$ be the canonical ring homomorphism.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Given an ideal I in R, let $S^{-1}I$ be the set of the fractions in $S^{-1}R$ whose numerator is in I.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] This is an ideal of $S^{-1}R,$ which is generated by *j*(*I*), and called the *localization* of I by S.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Many properties of ideals are either preserved by saturation and localization, or can be characterized by simpler properties of localization and saturation.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Let R be a commutative ring, S be a multiplicative set in R , and M be an R -module.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The **localization of the module** M by S , denoted $S^{-1}M$ , is an $S^{-1}R$ -module that is constructed exactly as the localization of R , except that the numerators of the fractions belong to M .
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] It is straightforward to check that these operations are well-defined, that is, they give the same result for different choices of representatives of fractions.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The proof of equivalence (up to a canonical isomorphism) can be done by showing that the two definitions satisfy the same universal property.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Since the tensor product is a right exact functor, this implies that localization by S maps exact sequences of R-modules to exact sequences of $S^{-1}R$ -modules.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] In other words, localization is an exact functor, and $S^{-1}R$ is a flat R-module.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] This flatness and the fact that localization solves a universal property make that localization preserves many properties of modules and rings, and is compatible with solutions of other universal properties.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] where $\operatorname {Ann}$ denotes annihilator, that is the ideal of the elements of the ring that map to zero all elements of the module.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The definition of a prime ideal implies immediately that the complement $S=R\setminus {\mathfrak {p}}$ of a prime ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}$ in a commutative ring R is a multiplicative set.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Again, the localization $S^{-1}M$ is commonly denoted $M_{\mathfrak {p}}$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Such localizations are fundamental for commutative algebra and algebraic geometry for several reasons.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] One is that local rings are often easier to study than general commutative rings, in particular because of Nakayama lemma.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] However, the main reason is that many properties are true for a ring if and only if they are true for all its local rings.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] For example, a ring is regular if and only if all its local rings are regular local rings.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Properties of a ring that can be characterized on its local rings are called *local properties*, and are often the algebraic counterpart of geometric local properties of algebraic varieties, which are properties that can be studied by restriction to a small neighborhood of each point of the variety.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] is a faithfully flat module when the direct sum is taken over all prime ideals (or over all maximal ideals of R).
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] On the other hand, some properties are not local properties.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] For example, an infinite direct product of fields is not an integral domain nor a Noetherian ring, while all its local rings are fields, and therefore Noetherian integral domains.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] Localizing non-commutative rings is more difficult.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] While the localization exists for every set *S* of prospective units, it might take a different form to the one described above.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] One condition which ensures that the localization is well behaved is the Ore condition.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] One case for non-commutative rings where localization has a clear interest is for rings of differential operators.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] It has the interpretation, for example, of adjoining a formal inverse *D*−1 for a differentiation operator *D*.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] This is done in many contexts in methods for differential equations.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] There is now a large mathematical theory about it, named microlocalization, connecting with numerous other branches.
[src:commutative-algebra/localization-commutative-algebra] The *micro-* tag is to do with connections with Fourier theory, in particular.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] In mathematics, a **Noetherian ring** is a ring that satisfies the ascending chain condition on left and right ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] If the chain condition is satisfied only for left ideals or for right ideals, then the ring is said **left-Noetherian** or **right-Noetherian** respectively.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] Equivalently, a ring is left-Noetherian (respectively right-Noetherian) if every left ideal (respectively right-ideal) is finitely generated.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] A ring is Noetherian if it is both left- and right-Noetherian.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] Noetherian rings are named after Emmy Noether, but the importance of the concept was recognized earlier by David Hilbert, with the proof of Hilbert's basis theorem (which asserts that polynomial rings are Noetherian) and Hilbert's syzygy theorem.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] For commutative rings, all three concepts coincide, but in general they are different.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] There are rings that are left-Noetherian and not right-Noetherian, and vice versa.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] Similar results hold for right-Noetherian rings.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] For a commutative ring to be Noetherian it suffices that every prime ideal of the ring is finitely generated.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] Rings that are not Noetherian tend to be (in some sense) very large.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] However, a non-Noetherian ring can be a subring of a Noetherian ring.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] Since any integral domain is a subring of a field, any integral domain that is not Noetherian provides an example.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] Indeed, there are rings that are right Noetherian, but not left Noetherian, so that one must be careful in measuring the "size" of a ring this way.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] For example, if *L* is a subgroup of **Q**2 isomorphic to **Z**, let *R* be the ring of homomorphisms *f* from **Q**2 to itself satisfying *f*(*L*) ⊂ *L*.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] This ring is right Noetherian, but not left Noetherian; the subset *I* ⊂ *R* consisting of elements with *a* = 0 and *γ* = 0 is a left ideal that is not finitely generated as a left *R*-module.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] If *R* is a commutative subring of a left Noetherian ring *S*, and *S* is finitely generated as a left *R*-module, then *R* is Noetherian.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] A unique factorization domain is not necessarily a Noetherian ring.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] It does satisfy a weaker condition: the ascending chain condition on principal ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] A ring of polynomials in infinitely-many variables is an example of a non-Noetherian unique factorization domain.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] A valuation ring is not Noetherian unless it is a principal ideal domain.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] It gives an example of a ring that arises naturally in algebraic geometry but is not Noetherian.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] Consider the group ring $R[G]$ of a group G over a ring R .
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] It is a ring, and an associative algebra over R if R is commutative.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] For a group G and a commutative ring R , the following two conditions are equivalent.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] If $R[G]$ is left/right/two-sided Noetherian, then R is left/right/two-sided Noetherian and G is a Noetherian group.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] Conversely, if R is a Noetherian commutative ring and G is an extension of a Noetherian solvable group (i.e. a polycyclic group) by a finite group, then $R[G]$ is two-sided Noetherian.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] On the other hand, however, there is a Noetherian group G whose group ring over any Noetherian commutative ring is not two-sided Noetherian.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] Many important theorems in ring theory (especially the theory of commutative rings) rely on the assumptions that the rings are Noetherian.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] Given a ring, there is a close connection between the behaviors of injective modules over the ring and whether the ring is a Noetherian ring or not.
[src:commutative-algebra/noetherian-ring] The endomorphism ring of an indecomposable injective module is local and thus Azumaya's theorem says that, over a left Noetherian ring, each indecomposable decomposition of an injective module is equivalent to one another (a variant of the Krull–Schmidt theorem).
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The theorem was first proven by Emanuel Lasker (1905) for the special case of polynomial rings and convergent power series rings, and was proven in its full generality by Emmy Noether (1921).
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The Lasker–Noether theorem is an extension of the fundamental theorem of arithmetic, and more generally the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups to all Noetherian rings.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The theorem plays an important role in algebraic geometry, by asserting that every algebraic set may be uniquely decomposed into a finite union of irreducible components.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] It has a straightforward extension to modules stating that every submodule of a finitely generated module over a Noetherian ring is a finite intersection of primary submodules.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] This contains the case for rings as a special case, considering the ring as a module over itself, so that ideals are submodules.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] This also generalizes the primary decomposition form of the structure theorem for finitely generated modules over a principal ideal domain, and for the special case of polynomial rings over a field, it generalizes the decomposition of an algebraic set into a finite union of (irreducible) varieties.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The first algorithm for computing primary decompositions for polynomial rings over a field of characteristic 0 was published by Noether's student Grete Hermann (1926).
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The decomposition does not hold in general for non-commutative Noetherian rings.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Noether gave an example of a non-commutative Noetherian ring with a right ideal that is not an intersection of primary ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] An ideal I of R is called **primary** if it is a proper ideal and for each pair of elements x and y in R such that $xy$ is in I , either x or some power of y is in I ; equivalently, every zero-divisor in the quotient $R/I$ is nilpotent.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The radical of a primary ideal Q is a prime ideal and Q is said to be ${\mathfrak {p}}$ -primary for ${\mathfrak {p}}={\sqrt {Q}}$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Primary ideals which correspond to non-minimal prime ideals over I are in general not unique (see an example below).
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] For the existence of the decomposition, see #Primary decomposition from associated primes below.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The elements of $\{{\sqrt {Q_{i}}}\mid i\}$ are called the **prime divisors** of I or the **primes belonging to** I .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] In the language of module theory, as discussed below, the set $\{{\sqrt {Q_{i}}}\mid i\}$ is also the set of associated primes of the R -module $R/I$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] By a way of shortcut, some authors call an associated prime of $R/I$ simply an associated prime of I (note this practice will conflict with the usage in the module theory).
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] In the case of the ring of integers $\mathbb {Z}$ , the Lasker–Noether theorem is equivalent to the fundamental theorem of arithmetic.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The examples of the section are designed for illustrating some properties of primary decompositions, which may appear as surprising or counter-intuitive.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] All examples are ideals in a polynomial ring over a field *k*.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Because of the generator of degree one, *I* is not the product of two larger ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] In $k[x,y]$ , the ideal $\langle x,y^{2}\rangle$ is a primary ideal that has $\langle x,y\rangle$ as associated prime.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] It is not a power of its associated prime.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The minimal prime is (*y*) and the embedded prime is (*x*, *y*).
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Unless for very simple examples, a primary decomposition may be hard to compute and may have a very complicated output.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The following example has been designed to provide just such a complicated output, while, nevertheless, being accessible to hand-written computation.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] be two homogeneous polynomials in *x*, *y*, whose coefficients $a_{1},\ldots ,a_{m},b_{0},\ldots ,b_{n}$ are polynomials in other indeterminates $z_{1},\ldots ,z_{h}$ over a field *k*.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] That is, *P* and *Q* belong to $R=k[x,y,z_{1},\ldots ,z_{h}],$ and it is in this ring that a primary decomposition of the ideal $I=\langle P,Q\rangle$ is searched.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] For computing the primary decomposition, we suppose first that 1 is a greatest common divisor of *P* and *Q*.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] This condition implies that *I* has no primary component of height one.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] As *I* is generated by two elements, this implies that it is a complete intersection (more precisely, it defines an algebraic set, which is a complete intersection), and thus all primary components have height two.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Therefore, the associated primes of *I* are exactly the primes ideals of height two that contain *I*.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] It follows that $\langle x,y\rangle$ is an associated prime of *I*.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Let $D\in k[z_{1},\ldots ,z_{h}]$ be the homogeneous resultant in *x*, *y* of *P* and *Q*.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] As the greatest common divisor of *P* and *Q* is a constant, the resultant *D* is not zero, and resultant theory implies that *I* contains all products of *D* by a monomial in *x*, *y* of degree *m* + *n* – 1.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] In short, we have a primary component, with the very simple associated prime $\langle x,y\rangle ,$ such all its generating sets involve all indeterminates.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The other primary component contains *D*.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] One may prove that if *P* and *Q* are sufficiently generic (for example if the coefficients of *P* and *Q* are distinct indeterminates), then there is only another primary component, which is a prime ideal, and is generated by *P*, *Q* and *D*.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] of *I* defines a decomposition of *V*(*I*) into a union of algebraic sets *V*(*Q**i*), which are irreducible, as not being the union of two smaller algebraic sets.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] where the union is restricted to minimal associated primes.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] These minimal associated primes are the primary components of the radical of *I*.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] For this reason, the primary decomposition of the radical of *I* is sometimes called the *prime decomposition* of *I*.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The components of a primary decomposition (as well as of the algebraic set decomposition) corresponding to minimal primes are said *isolated*, and the others are said *embedded*.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] For the decomposition of algebraic varieties, only the minimal primes are interesting, but in intersection theory, and, more generally in scheme theory, the complete primary decomposition has a geometric meaning.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Nowadays, it is common to do primary decomposition of ideals and modules within the theory of **associated primes**.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Bourbaki's influential textbook *Algèbre commutative*, in particular, takes this approach.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] By definition, an **associated prime** is a prime ideal which is the annihilator of a nonzero element of M ; that is, ${\mathfrak {p}}=\operatorname {Ann} (m)$ for some $m\in M$ (this implies $m\neq 0$ ).
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Equivalently, a prime ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}$ is an associated prime of M if there is an injection of R -modules $R/{\mathfrak {p}}\hookrightarrow M$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] A maximal element of the set of annihilators of nonzero elements of M can be shown to be a prime ideal and thus, when R is a Noetherian ring, there exists an associated prime of M if and only if M is nonzero.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The set of associated primes of M is denoted by $\operatorname {Ass} _{R}(M)$ or $\operatorname {Ass} (M)$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] such that each quotient $M_{i}/M_{i-1}$ is isomorphic to $R/{\mathfrak {p}}_{i}$ for some prime ideals ${\mathfrak {p}}_{i}$ , each of which is necessarily in the support of M .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] (In general, these inclusions are not the equalities.) In particular, $\operatorname {Ass} (M)$ is a finite set when M is finitely generated.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Let M be a finitely generated module over a Noetherian ring R and N a submodule of M .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] A submodule N of M is called *${\mathfrak {p}}$ -primary* if $\operatorname {Ass} (M/N)=\{{\mathfrak {p}}\}$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] A submodule of the R -module R is ${\mathfrak {p}}$ -primary as a submodule if and only if it is a ${\mathfrak {p}}$ -primary ideal; thus, when $M=R$ , the above decomposition is precisely a primary decomposition of an ideal.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The next theorem gives necessary and sufficient conditions for a ring to have primary decompositions for its ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The proof is given at Chapter 4 of Atiyah–Macdonald as a series of exercises.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] There is the following uniqueness theorem for an ideal having a primary decomposition.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The set of minimal elements of E is the same as the set of minimal prime ideals over I .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Moreover, the primary ideal corresponding to a minimal prime ${\mathfrak {p}}$ is the pre-image of I $R_{\mathfrak {p}}$ and thus is uniquely determined by I .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Now, for any commutative ring R , an ideal I and a minimal prime ${\mathfrak {p}}$ over I , the pre-image of $I\,R_{\mathfrak {p}}$ under the localization map is the smallest ${\mathfrak {p}}$ -primary ideal containing I .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] Thus, in the setting of preceding theorem, the primary ideal ${\mathfrak {q}}$ corresponding to a minimal prime ${\mathfrak {p}}$ is also the smallest ${\mathfrak {p}}$ -primary ideal containing I and is called the ${\mathfrak {p}}$ -primary component of I .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] For example, if the power ${\mathfrak {p}}^{n}$ of a prime ${\mathfrak {p}}$ has a primary decomposition, then its ${\mathfrak {p}}$ -primary component is the n -th symbolic power of ${\mathfrak {p}}$ .
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] This result is the first in an area now known as the additive theory of ideals, which studies the ways of representing an ideal as the intersection of a special class of ideals.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] The decision on the "special class", e.g., primary ideals, is a problem in itself.
[src:commutative-algebra/primary-decomposition] In the case of non-commutative rings, the class of tertiary ideals is a useful substitute for the class of primary ideals.
